    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1981-01-26T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1981-01-26T00:00:00-05:00" n="257"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d257">
                <head>257. Letter From Secretary of State <persName corresp="#p_HAM_1"
                        >Haig</persName> to the Director of the Office of Management and Budget
                        (<persName corresp="#p_SDA_1">Stockman</persName>)<note n="1" type="source"
                        xml:id="d257fn1">Source: Reagan Library, Executive Secretariat, <gloss
                            target="#t_NSC_1">NSC</gloss> Subject File, [Security Assistance]
                        Foreign Aid (February 1981); NLR–753–92–10–2–7. Confidential.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>Washington</placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian"
                            when="1981-01-26">January 26, 1981</date>
                    </dateline>
                    <salute>Dear Dave:</salute>
                </opener>
                <p>I understand that the <gloss target="#t_OMB_1">OMB</gloss> review of the
                        <persName corresp="#p_CJEJ_1">Carter</persName> Administration’s <gloss
                        target="#t_FY_1">FY</gloss> 82 budget proposal could affect the status of
                    many of our foreign affairs programs. Some of these programs—security and
                    development assistance in particular—are as important to <gloss target="#t_US_1"
                        >U.S.</gloss> national security as many items in the defense budget.</p>
                <p>It may well be that there is room for reductions in certain programs; indeed, I
                    expect this to be the case. However, I know you agree that policy must drive
                    these resource decisions, and we are only just beginning the <persName
                        corresp="#p_RRW_1">Reagan</persName> Administration’s review of <gloss
                        target="#t_US_1">U.S.</gloss> national security policy.</p>
                <p>In general, I believe that critical State Department and foreign assistance
                    programs which relate to our national security policy should be treated in the
                    same way as defense programs. These programs fall into three principal
                    categories: <list>
                        <label>—</label>
                        <item>Properly tailored security assistance, which enables our friends and
                            Allies to take on defense tasks which otherwise we would have to assume
                            ourselves;</item>
                        <label>—</label>
                        <item>Economic assistance programs, which are one of the key tools available
                            to us to promote regional stability, particularly for some of our
                            principal recipients such as Egypt and Israel;</item>
                        <label>—</label>
                        <item>Functions carried out by State Department personnel
                            overseas—intelligence, negotiations for base access and overflight
                            rights, arranging military exercises, etc.—which are of direct value to
                            our defense posture.</item>
                    </list>
                </p>
                <pb facs="0699" n="654" xml:id="pg_654"/>
                <p>Pending a more thorough review, I believe such matters should be treated as
                    defense items in any <gloss target="#t_OMB_1">OMB</gloss> budget review,
                    particularly since we are already starting with levels of security assistance
                    that were cut badly by the <persName corresp="#p_CJEJ_1">Carter</persName>
                    Administration.</p>
                <p>Sincerely,</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_HAM_1">
                            <hi rend="strong">Alexander M. Haig, Jr.</hi>
                        </persName>
                        <note n="2" xml:id="d257fn2">
                            <persName corresp="#p_HAM_1">Haig</persName> signed “Al” above his typed
                            signature.</note>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
